ity of new technologies—notably film, sound recording, and photography—to reproduce works of art in great number. Benjamin could not have foreseen the explosion of imagery and media that has occurred during the past fifty years. Does Benjamin’s famous essay still speak to this new situation? That is the question posed by the editors of this book to a wide range of leading scholars and thinkers across a spectrum of disciplines in the humanities. The essays gathered here do not hazard a univocal reply to that question; rather they offer a rich, wide-ranging critique of Benjamin’s position that refracts and reflects contemporary thinking about the ethical, political, and aesthetic implications of life in the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaecker, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBann, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarck, Karlheinz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehnke, Kerstin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolz, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartier, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinstein, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilgen, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGumbrecht, Hans Ulrich, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarrison, Robert P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennion, Antoine, econtributor.4ct